> 2493: \subsection{Distinguishability Between Embedding outputs of Different Patients}
  2494: This section evaluates the efficacy of the proposed defense mechanism by processing some patient samples through a client model in both protected and unprotected states. The primary objective is to determine whether the defense successfully prevents a malicious server from receiving distinct embedding outputs, thereby complicating unauthorized data recovery. For visualization purposes, we employed a perturbation level of $\epsilon = 10$. As this represents the lower bound of noise integration within our study at which BVFLMSP maintained highest performance among all privacy budgets. So, if differential privacy is preserved at this threshold, it is inherently guaranteed for all larger noise parameters that we investigated.

