>  228: \subsubsection{L1-balance outside of a Tile}
   229: We finally demonstrate that a single \gls{te} is not bound by the hierarchical interconnect to the distributed L1-memory in other Tiles. To further simplify the calculation, we assume that the \glspl{te}' 512-bit wide accesses all have a random starting address. The assumption works well when the matrices are large enough to be well distributed across all memory banks and when the Xs and Ws do not overlap, which can be easily avoided using the workload mapping strategies explained later in \Cref{sec:performance}. We indicate with $N_{B}=2048$ and $N_{B/T}=32$ the total banks of TensorPool and the banks in a Tile. We first compute the probability of local and remote access ($p_{loc.}$ and $p_{rem.}$). We then combine the bandwidth to banks within a Tile and the bandwidth to remote locations (through the Tile's arbiter), to compute the total bandwidth for a \gls{te} ($\beta$) and the complete (local and remote access) Kung's inequality.

