> 1597: \paragraph{Ambiguous parameterization and the prior problem.} Neural network parameterizations exhibit multiple symmetries and non-identifiabilities (e.g., permutations of hidden units, sign/scale symmetries in certain architectures, and flat directions in function space). As a consequence, a seemingly weakly informative prior in parameter space, such as $\theta\sim\mathcal{N}(0,\sigma^2 I)$, can induce a highly nontrivial and sometimes undesirable distribution over functions. When parameters are non-physical, the practical question becomes: which prior produces a sensible prior predictive behavior?
