- file: sample\arxiv_sources\2604.02315v1\colm2026_conference.tex (line 600)
  error: Theory of mind in LLMs.
  message: Should this be "Theory of Mind in LLMs."? Follow your preferred style guide and register as an exception if necessary.
   599: 
>  600: \paragraph{Theory of mind in LLMs.}
   601: Evaluating whether LLMs can attribute beliefs and intentions to others has produced a consistent finding: models pass explicit belief-attribution probes but fail when the same reasoning must be expressed behaviorally \citep{sap2022neural, kim-etal-2023-fantom, ma-etal-2023-towards-holistic}. \citet{gu2024simpletom} make this precise: frontier models achieve $>95\%$ on mental-state inference yet drop below $50\%$ on behavior prediction and below $20\%$ on judgment. This illustrates ``knowing versus applying'' dissociation. Our accuracy vs followup gap is structurally analogous, but where SimpleToM probes reasoning about \emph{another agent's} mental state (third-person inference), we probe whether a model encodes the consequence of \emph{its own} response (first-person behavioral readout). Both converge on the same conclusion: solving the immediate task does not guarantee modeling what comes next.

- file: sample\arxiv_sources\2604.02315v1\colm2026_conference.tex (line 603)
  error: User simulation.
  message: Should this be "User Simulation."? Follow your preferred style guide and register as an exception if necessary.
   602: 
>  603: \paragraph{User simulation.}
   604: User simulation has a long history in dialogue systems \citep{schatzmann2007agenda, ShiQWY19}, and same-model self-play has been used for data generation and evaluation \citep{ghandeharioun2019approximating, xu2023baize}. Recent work builds dedicated user proxies: \citet{naous2026flipping} train user models by flipping dialogue turns, \citet{dou2025simulatorarena} benchmark simulator reliability, \citet{hathidara2026mirrorbench} evaluate human-likeness, and \citet{zhou2026sim2real} show that current simulators are overly cooperative and inflate agent scores. Our goal is different: we do not build a reusable user proxy but use user-turn generation as a \emph{probe} of the assistant model's own weights. A high-quality external simulator does not imply that the assistant itself possesses interaction awareness. The failure modes we catalog (prompt restatement, meta-planning, identity leakage) characterize the same behaviors \citet{zhou2026sim2real} observe when assistant models are repurposed as user proxies without dedicated training.

- file: sample\arxiv_sources\2604.02315v1\colm2026_conference.tex (line 606)
  error: Multi-turn optimization and interaction-aware training.
  message: Should this be "Multi-Turn Optimization and Interaction-Aware Training."? Follow your preferred style guide and register as an exception if necessary.
   605: 
>  606: \paragraph{Multi-turn optimization and interaction-aware training.}
   607: Standard post-training optimizes the current response via single-turn preferences or rewards \citep{ouyang2022training, rafailov2023direct}. Recent work extends the training signal beyond the current turn: \citet{wu2025collabllm} optimize for future collaboration quality via forward-sampled multiturn rollouts, \citet{buening2026aligning} use post-action user states as supervision, ArCHer \citep{archer} applies hierarchical multi-turn RL, and \citet{wang2026openclaw} frame every agent interaction as producing a ``next-state signal'' that encodes evaluative and directive information for online learning. In multi-agent RL, \citet{monwilliams2025partner} show that partner models emerge in recurrent agents but only when the environment provides influence over partner behavior, a conditional emergence paralleled by our perturbation results (\S\ref{sec:perturbation-results}), where interaction awareness surfaces only under specific contextual cues. These methods share a premise that the user's reaction carries training signal. Our work provides an evaluation lens for the capability they target: the genuine-followup metric measures the next-state signal that \citet{wang2026openclaw} propose to harness and the collaboration quality that \citet{wu2025collabllm} optimize for, but from an evaluation point of view. Our post-training experiments (\S\ref{sec:post-training-results}) validate this connection, confirming that multiturn collaboration training induces measurable interaction awareness as a side effect.

- file: sample\arxiv_sources\2604.02315v1\colm2026_conference.tex (line 609)
  error: Interactive benchmarks.
  message: Should this be "Interactive Benchmarks."? Follow your preferred style guide and register as an exception if necessary.
   608: 
>  609: \paragraph{Interactive benchmarks.}
   610: $\tau^2$-Bench \citep{barres2025tau2}, and CRMArena \citep{huang2025crmarena-pro} evaluate agents in tool-mediated settings with simulated users and task-level rewards, embedding consequence modeling in richer environments. Proactive dialogue work \citep{proactive_survey, star_gate, interactive_text_gen} similarly argues that agents must model the interaction trajectory. Our probe is narrower and this simplicity enables attribution of differences to model weights and training rather than environment confounds. A model that fails our probe lacks the interaction awareness needed for the richer settings these benchmarks target.

- file: sample\arxiv_sources\2604.02315v1\colm2026_conference.tex (line 617)
  error: Single-turn training data.
  message: Should this be "Single-Turn Training Data."? Follow your preferred style guide and register as an exception if necessary.
   616: 
>  617: \paragraph{Single-turn training data.}
   618: Models post-trained predominantly on single-turn (query, response) pairs will have learned that the most likely token sequence under the user role is a new query, not a follow-up to the preceding response. Under this explanation, the low follow-up rate is a distributional artifact rather than evidence about what the model's representations encode. We view this as complementary to our framing: if the training data did not include multi-turn continuations, then the model's training did not instill interaction awareness, which is precisely the gap we identify. The post-training results (\S\ref{sec:post-training-results}) directly test this: collaboration-oriented training on multi-turn data raises follow-up rates, confirming that the training distribution is a causal factor.

- file: sample\arxiv_sources\2604.02315v1\colm2026_conference.tex (line 620)
  error: Chat template conventions.
  message: Should this be "Chat Template Conventions."? Follow your preferred style guide and register as an exception if necessary.
   619: 
>  620: \paragraph{Chat template conventions.}
   621: The \texttt{<|im\_end|>} token after the assistant turn may function as a strong ``conversation complete'' signal in some training pipelines, biasing the model toward starting a new exchange rather than continuing the current one. If this were the sole explanation, we would expect all models using the same chat template to show similar follow-up rates. However, within the Qwen3.5 family (which shares a template), follow-up rates vary from $0.0\%$ to $13.1\%$ across model sizes and datasets. Cross-family, \texttt{gpt-oss} models produce substantially higher follow-up than Qwen models of comparable or larger size on GPQA, despite all models using role-delimited chat formats. The perturbation results further argue against a purely template-level explanation: truncation and explicit-question perturbations change \texttt{gpt-oss} and \texttt{GLM} follow-up rates substantially while leaving Qwen largely unaffected (\S\ref{sec:perturbation-results}).

- file: sample\arxiv_sources\2604.02315v1\colm2026_conference.tex (line 623)
  error: Role-header semantics.
  message: Should this be "Role-Header Semantics."? Follow your preferred style guide and register as an exception if necessary.
   622: 
>  623: \paragraph{Role-header semantics.}
   624: Different model families may have been trained with different conventions for what follows a user-role header (a new independent query versus a continuation of the same conversation). We do not have access to the post-training data for any of the evaluated models, so we cannot rule this out entirely. However, we control for it indirectly through the held-out evaluation setting (\S\ref{sec:experimental-setup}), where the model generates a user turn given a real multi-turn conversation context. On HealthBench and Coval, follow-up rates are substantially higher ($19$--$48\%$) than on benchmark datasets, suggesting that when the conversational context is richer, even models with low benchmark follow-up rates can produce grounded continuations. This is consistent with interaction awareness being latent but context-dependent, rather than absent.

- file: sample\arxiv_sources\2604.02315v1\colm2026_conference.tex (line 626)
  error: Behavioral versus representational claims.
  message: Should this be "Behavioral Versus Representational Claims."? Follow your preferred style guide and register as an exception if necessary.
   625: 
>  626: \paragraph{Behavioral versus representational claims.}
   627: We emphasize that our probe measures the model's \emph{behavioral} output under the user role, not its internal representations. A model could in principle encode rich conversational structure internally while still producing restatement as the modal continuation, if its training objective did not incentivize expressing that structure under the user role. Representation-level analyses (e.g., probing internal activations for next-turn content) would complement the behavioral probe we propose. Our claims are therefore about what the model \emph{produces}, conditioned on the experimental setup, rather than about the totality of what the model \emph{knows}. We view this as a feature of the probe rather than a limitation: deployment-relevant interaction awareness must ultimately manifest in generated text, not only in latent representations.

